Note:
Markdown Lexer - CommonMark compliant tokenization

This file provides lexical analysis for Markdown documents following
the CommonMark specification with GitHub Flavored Markdown (GFM) extensions.

Markdown Structure:
- Block-level elements (headings, paragraphs, lists, code blocks, blockquotes)
- Inline elements (emphasis, strong, links, images, inline code)
- Both ATX headings (# Heading) and Setext headings (underlined)
- Ordered and unordered lists with nesting
- Fenced code blocks with language tags
- Blockquotes with nesting
- Tables (GFM extension)
- Horizontal rules
- HTML blocks (passthrough)

Token Types:
- Structure tokens (heading, list marker, code fence, blockquote)
- Inline tokens (emphasis, strong, link, image, code)
- Text content tokens
- Whitespace and line breaks

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 0
Constant TOKEN_NEWLINE as Integer is 1

Note: Block-level tokens
Constant TOKEN_HEADING as Integer is 10       Note: # Heading
Constant TOKEN_PARAGRAPH as Integer is 11     Note: Text paragraph
Constant TOKEN_CODE_FENCE as Integer is 12    Note: ``` or ~~~
Constant TOKEN_CODE_BLOCK as Integer is 13    Note: Indented code block
Constant TOKEN_BLOCKQUOTE as Integer is 14    Note: is greater than Quote
Constant TOKEN_LIST_ITEM as Integer is 15     Note: minus or multiplied by or plus or 1.
Constant TOKEN_HORIZONTAL_RULE as Integer is 16  Note: --- or *** or ___
Constant TOKEN_HTML_BLOCK as Integer is 17    Note: <tag>

Note: Inline tokens
Constant TOKEN_TEXT as Integer is 20          Note: Plain text
Constant TOKEN_EMPHASIS as Integer is 21      Note: *text* or _text_
Constant TOKEN_STRONG as Integer is 22        Note: **text** or __text__
Constant TOKEN_CODE as Integer is 23          Note: `code`
Constant TOKEN_LINK as Integer is 24          Note: [text](url)
Constant TOKEN_IMAGE as Integer is 25         Note: ![alt](url)
Constant TOKEN_AUTOLINK as Integer is 26      Note: <url>
Constant TOKEN_LINE_BREAK as Integer is 27    Note: Two spaces plus newline

Note: Table tokens (GFM)
Constant TOKEN_TABLE_ROW as Integer is 30
Constant TOKEN_TABLE_DELIMITER as Integer is 31
Constant TOKEN_TABLE_CELL as Integer is 32

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Token record carries a type tag, a pointer/length slice into the source buffer
(non-owning for plain text, owned heap for buffers built by inline scanners
that need to strip the closing delimiter), 1-based diagnostic line/column, and
a polymorphic metadata slot reused by structural tokens (heading level 1-6,
list ordered/unordered flag, fence run length). Six fixed int64 slots keep the
struct power-of-two sized at 48 bytes for arena-cache alignment.
@End Reasoning
Type called "Token":
    type as Integer           Note: Token type constant
    lexeme as Integer         Note: Pointer to token text
    lexeme_length as Integer  Note: Length of token text
    line as Integer           Note: Line number
    column as Integer         Note: Column number
    metadata as Integer       Note: Additional data (heading level, list type, etc.)
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lexer state carries the source pointer/length pair (cached so character-access
hot paths skip a string_length call per byte), the byte cursor, 1-based
line/column for diagnostics, and an at_line_start flag that CommonMark requires
for block-level token disambiguation (an unindented heading marker is only a
heading when at_line_start = 1). The flag is reset by newline and cleared by
any non-whitespace byte.
@End Reasoning
Type called "MarkdownLexer":
    source as Integer          Note: Source code pointer
    source_length as Integer   Note: Source code length
    position as Integer        Note: Current position
    line as Integer            Note: Current line
    column as Integer          Note: Current column
    at_line_start as Integer   Note: Boolean: at start of line
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructor seeds the lexer at the document start: position=0, line=1, col=1,
at_line_start=1 (the first byte of any document is by definition the start of
a line, so an opening "# Heading" is recognized as a heading).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 48 bytes (6 int64 fields), caches source_length via string_length to
avoid recomputing it on every peek, and returns 0 on allocation failure so the
caller can propagate the OOM condition.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_markdown_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create Markdown lexer

    Let lexer_size be 48  Note: MarkdownLexer: 6 fields × 8 bytes
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    Note: Initialize lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0  Note: position = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1  Note: line = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1  Note: column = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 1  Note: at_line_start = true

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Destructor releases the lexer struct itself; the source buffer is caller-owned
and intentionally not freed here, and emitted tokens retain their own buffer
ownership independently of the lexer's lifetime.
@End Reasoning
Process called "destroy_markdown_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy Markdown lexer

    If lexer is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Access
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Pure read; never mutates position/line/column or at_line_start. Returning 0 on
position >= source_length collapses physical EOF and the literal null byte to
the same sentinel — Markdown documents must not legally contain NUL, so this
ambiguity is acceptable for a text-format lexer.
@End Reasoning

@Performance_Hints:
Hot path called by every block- and inline-scanner. O(1): one int64 load for
position, one for source_length, one byte load. No allocation, no string ops.
@End Performance_Hints
Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current character without consuming

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lookahead at position+offset without mutation. Used by inline scanners to peek
at the second byte of "![" (image start) and ahead of the cursor for emphasis
delimiter run counting before committing to a tokenization path.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_char_at" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at character at offset from current position

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let look_ahead_pos be position plus offset
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If look_ahead_pos is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, look_ahead_pos

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
The single mutating cursor primitive. Owns the entire position/line/column and
at_line_start update protocol: newline resets column to 1 and at_line_start to
1; any non-whitespace byte (not space, not tab) clears at_line_start since
indented continuation whitespace must keep block-start eligibility live for
the first non-whitespace marker on the line.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read-then-increment so the returned character is the one just consumed. Bytes
beyond source_length return 0 without advancing position past the end, so
repeated calls at EOF are idempotent.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume current character and advance position

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position

    Note: Update line and column
    If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1  Note: column = 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 1  Note: at_line_start = true
    Otherwise:
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        Set column to column plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column

        If char is not equal to 32:  Note: not space
            If char is not equal to 9:  Note: not tab
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0  Note: at_line_start = false
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return char
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
CommonMark distinguishes "whitespace" (space U+0020, tab U+0009) from line
terminators. List-marker scanners require a whitespace byte immediately after
the marker to commit to TOKEN_LIST_ITEM, so this predicate must not be widened
to include newlines.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace (space or tab)

    If char is equal to 32:  Note: space
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 9:  Note: tab
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recognizes both LF (Unix) and CR (legacy Mac / first byte of Windows CRLF).
The CRLF pair is handled by next_token, which emits a single NEWLINE token on
the CR and then absorbs a following LF; this predicate just answers "is this
byte a line terminator".
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_newline" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is newline

    If char is equal to 10:  Note: \n
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 13:  Note: \r
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII 48..57 range check. Markdown's ordered-list grammar only accepts ASCII
digits, so this deliberately rejects Unicode digit categories (e.g. Arabic-
Indic numerals) which CommonMark does not treat as list markers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is digit 0-9

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        If char is less than or equal to 57:  Note: '9'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII letter range check (A..Z, a..z). Used by future autolink scheme detection
and HTML block tag matching; underscore is intentionally excluded here even
though it is a delimiter for emphasis because emphasis processing has its own
specialized scanner.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 65:  Note: 'A'
        If char is less than or equal to 90:  Note: 'Z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:  Note: 'a'
        If char is less than or equal to 122:  Note: 'z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Centralized token constructor — every scanner emits through here so the field
layout (type/lexeme/length/line/column/metadata) stays a single point of
change. Diagnostic line/column are captured from caller-supplied values rather
than the current lexer state because the caller saved them BEFORE consuming
the marker (e.g. heading's "#" column, not the column after the marker run).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 48 bytes, writes six int64 slots in declared order, and propagates
allocator OOM (returns 0) so callers can free auxiliary buffers and bail.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, lexeme as Integer, length as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer, metadata as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token with all fields

    Let token_size be 48  Note: Token: 6 fields × 8 bytes
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 40, metadata

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Line Processing Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Counts visual indentation in space-equivalents, consuming the whitespace as it
goes. The 4-space tab expansion follows CommonMark section 2.2: a tab advances
the indent counter to the next multiple-of-4 column; this implementation
simplifies that to a flat +4 per tab, which is correct for the common case of
tabs only appearing at the start of a line.
@End Reasoning
Process called "count_leading_spaces" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Count leading spaces/tabs at current position (4 spaces = 1 tab)

    Let count be 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 32:  Note: space
            Set count to count plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 9:  Note: tab
            Set count to count plus 4  Note: Tab counts as 4 spaces
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return count
End Process

@Reasoning:
Inline whitespace skipper — discards spaces and tabs without crossing line
boundaries. Used after a heading or list marker to find the start of the
content, so newlines must remain visible to the caller as terminators.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip spaces and tabs (not newlines)

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 32:  Note: space
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 9:  Note: tab
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Advances the cursor up to but not including the next newline (or EOF). Leaves
the newline in place so next_token will subsequently emit TOKEN_NEWLINE and
reset at_line_start for the following line's block-level scanning.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_to_end_of_line" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip to end of current line

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Block-Level Token Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
ATX heading recognizer. Counts up to six leading '#' bytes (CommonMark caps
heading depth at 6), skips one or more separating spaces, then captures the
rest of the line as the heading text. The level (1..6) is stored in the
token's metadata slot. Zero '#' bytes returns 0 to let the caller fall through
to text-token scanning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
The non-owning lexeme slice is a pointer into the source buffer plus a length,
so heading text shares storage with the document and does not require a copy.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_heading" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan ATX heading: # Heading

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    Note: Count # characters
    Let level be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 35:  Note: #
            Set level to level plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer

            If level is greater than 6:  Note: Max 6 levels
                Break
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    If level is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Not a heading
    End If

    If level is greater than 6:
        Set level to 6  Note: Cap at 6
    End If

    Note: Skip space after #
    proc skip_whitespace with lexer

    Note: Get heading text
    Let text_start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    proc skip_to_end_of_line with lexer
    Let text_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    Let text_length be text_end minus text_start
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let text_ptr be source plus text_start

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_HEADING, text_ptr, text_length, line, column, level
End Process

@Reasoning:
Fenced code block opener. CommonMark requires a run of at least three backticks
or tildes; the run length is stored in metadata so the parser can match the
closing fence, which must use the same character and at least the same count.
The optional language tag after the opening fence is captured as the token's
lexeme (used for syntax highlighting downstream).
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_code_fence" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan fenced code block: ``` or ~~~

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    Let fence_char be proc peek_char with lexer  Note: ` or ~

    Note: Count fence characters (must be at least 3)
    Let fence_count be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to fence_char:
            Set fence_count to fence_count plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    If fence_count is less than 3:
        Return 0  Note: Not a code fence
    End If

    Note: Get language tag (optional)
    proc skip_whitespace with lexer
    Let lang_start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    proc skip_to_end_of_line with lexer
    Let lang_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    Let lang_length be lang_end minus lang_start
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let lang_ptr be source plus lang_start

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_CODE_FENCE, lang_ptr, lang_length, line, column, fence_count
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a single TOKEN_BLOCKQUOTE for the leading '>' marker on a line. The
parser is responsible for grouping consecutive blockquote-prefixed lines into
a containing block; this lexer just hands it one marker per line. Trailing
whitespace after '>' is consumed to align the cursor with the actual content.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_blockquote" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan blockquote marker: >

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    If char is not equal to 62:  Note: >
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc skip_whitespace with lexer

    Let marker_text be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with ">"

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_BLOCKQUOTE, marker_text, 1, line, column, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recognizes both unordered ("-", "*", "+") and ordered ("1.") list markers. A
marker is only valid if followed by whitespace — otherwise "-rebase" or "*ptr"
would be misclassified. metadata distinguishes 0 (unordered) vs 1 (ordered)
so the parser knows whether to emit OL or UL containers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For ordered markers the entire digit run plus the trailing "." is captured as
the lexeme so the parser can recover the starting number for OL "start"
attribute generation.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_list_marker" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan list item marker: - or * or + or 1.

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    Note: Check for unordered list markers
    If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let next_char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If proc is_whitespace with next_char is equal to 1:
            Let marker_text be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "-"
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LIST_ITEM, marker_text, 1, line, column, 0  Note: 0 = unordered
        End If
    End If

    If char is equal to 42:  Note: *
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_char to proc peek_char with lexer

        If proc is_whitespace with next_char is equal to 1:
            Set marker_text to proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "*"
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LIST_ITEM, marker_text, 1, line, column, 0  Note: 0 = unordered
        End If
    End If

    If char is equal to 43:  Note: +
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_char to proc peek_char with lexer

        If proc is_whitespace with next_char is equal to 1:
            Set marker_text to proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "+"
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LIST_ITEM, marker_text, 1, line, column, 0  Note: 0 = unordered
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for ordered list markers (digit followed by . or ))
    If proc is_digit with char is equal to 1:
        Let number_start be start_position

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let digit_char be proc peek_char with lexer

            If proc is_digit with digit_char is equal to 1:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While

        Let marker_char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If marker_char is equal to 46:  Note: .
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Set next_char to proc peek_char with lexer

            If proc is_whitespace with next_char is equal to 1:
                Let current_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
                Let marker_length be current_position minus number_start
                Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
                Let marker_ptr be source plus number_start

                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LIST_ITEM, marker_ptr, marker_length, line, column, 1  Note: 1 = ordered
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Not a list marker
End Process

@Reasoning:
Horizontal rule requires three or more identical marker characters from
{'-', '*', '_'} with only optional whitespace between them, terminated by end
of line or EOF. Mixing markers ("-*-") is rejected per CommonMark, as is a
non-whitespace, non-marker byte appearing in the run.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_horizontal_rule" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan horizontal rule: --- or *** or ___

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer
    Let rule_char be 0
    Let count be 0

    Note: Determine rule character (-, *, or _)
    If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        Set rule_char to 45
    Otherwise If char is equal to 42:  Note: *
        Set rule_char to 42
    Otherwise If char is equal to 95:  Note: _
        Set rule_char to 95
    Otherwise:
        Return 0  Note: Not a horizontal rule
    End If

    Note: Count occurrences (must be at least 3)
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current_char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If current_char is equal to rule_char:
            Set count to count plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise If proc is_whitespace with current_char is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    If count is less than 3:
        Return 0  Note: Not enough characters
    End If

    Note: Must be end of line or EOF
    Let end_char be proc peek_char with lexer

    If end_char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
        Let rule_text be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "---"
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_HORIZONTAL_RULE, rule_text, 3, line, column, 0
    End If

    If proc is_newline with end_char is equal to 1:
        Set rule_text to proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "---"
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_HORIZONTAL_RULE, rule_text, 3, line, column, 0
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Not a horizontal rule
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Inline Element Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-backtick inline code scanner. Allocates a 512-byte working buffer for
the literal content; characters beyond that are silently truncated, which is
acceptable because legitimate inline code spans rarely exceed half a kilobyte.
On unterminated code (EOF before closing backtick) the buffer is freed and 0
is returned so the caller can fall back to literal-text tokenization.
@End Reasoning

@Security_Scope:
Inline code content is captured verbatim; downstream HTML emission is
responsible for entity-escaping. This scanner performs no transformation.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scan_inline_code" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan inline code: `code`

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Skip opening backtick
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let buffer_size be 512
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Return 0  Note: Unterminated code
        End If

        If char is equal to 96:  Note: ` (closing backtick)
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Break
        End If

        If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_CODE, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Combined emphasis ("*x*", "_x_") and strong ("**x**", "__x__") scanner. Counts
the opening delimiter run, captures content up to a matching closing run of
the same character, and uses TOKEN_STRONG vs TOKEN_EMPHASIS based on whether
the run count is >=2. A newline inside the span aborts, matching CommonMark's
rule that inline formatting does not cross block boundaries.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
When a partial run of closing markers is found (fewer than the opening count),
the lexer position is restored to the pre-scan point and the original markers
are appended to the buffer as literal characters; this preserves source text
while letting the outer scan continue searching for a valid close.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_emphasis_or_strong" takes lexer as Integer, marker_char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan emphasis or strong: * or ** or _ or __

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Count marker characters
    Let marker_count be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to marker_char:
            Set marker_count to marker_count plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer

            If marker_count is greater than or equal to 2:
                Break  Note: ** or __ for strong
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    If marker_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Scan content until closing marker
    Let buffer_size be 512
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let closing_count be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Return 0  Note: Unterminated emphasis/strong
        End If

        If char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline ends inline formatting
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Check for closing marker
        If char is equal to marker_char:
            Set closing_count to 0
            Let temp_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let check_char be proc peek_char with lexer

                If check_char is equal to marker_char:
                    Set closing_count to closing_count plus 1
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While

            If closing_count is greater than or equal to marker_count:
                Break  Note: Found closing marker
            Otherwise:
                Note: Not enough markers, restore position and add to content
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, temp_pos

                If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, marker_char
                    Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                End If

                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            End If

            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Note: Determine token type (emphasis or strong)
    Let token_type be TOKEN_EMPHASIS

    If marker_count is greater than or equal to 2:
        Set token_type to TOKEN_STRONG
    End If

    Return proc create_token with token_type, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unified scanner for "[text](url)" links and "![alt](url)" images. The token
lexeme is a single combined buffer of the form "text\0url\0" so a downstream
consumer can find both parts with two C-string reads; metadata stores text_pos
(the length of the text portion) so the URL portion can be located in O(1).
A newline anywhere inside either component aborts and returns 0, matching
CommonMark's restriction that link and image syntax does not span lines.
@End Reasoning

@Security_Scope:
URL content is captured verbatim; any URL-scheme filtering (e.g. blocking
"javascript:" in HTML emission) is the parser/renderer's responsibility, not
the lexer's.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scan_link_or_image" takes lexer as Integer, is_image as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan link [text](url) or image ![alt](url)

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Skip ! for image
    If is_image is equal to 1:
        proc advance_char with lexer  Note: !
    End If

    Note: Skip [
    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    If char is not equal to 91:  Note: [
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_char with lexer

    Note: Scan text/alt
    Let text_buffer_size be 512
    Let text_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with text_buffer_size
    Let text_pos be 0

    If text_buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            proc deallocate from Layout with text_buffer
            Return 0
        End If

        If char is equal to 93:  Note: ] (end of text)
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
            proc deallocate from Layout with text_buffer
            Return 0
        End If

        If text_pos is less than text_buffer_size:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with text_buffer, text_pos, char
            Set text_pos to text_pos plus 1
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with text_buffer, text_pos, 0

    Note: Check for (url)
    Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

    If char is not equal to 40:  Note: (
        proc deallocate from Layout with text_buffer
        Return 0  Note: Not a link/image
    End If

    proc advance_char with lexer

    Note: Scan URL
    Let url_buffer_size be 512
    Let url_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with url_buffer_size
    Let url_pos be 0

    If url_buffer is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with text_buffer
        Return 0
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            proc deallocate from Layout with text_buffer
            proc deallocate from Layout with url_buffer
            Return 0
        End If

        If char is equal to 41:  Note: ) (end of URL)
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
            proc deallocate from Layout with text_buffer
            proc deallocate from Layout with url_buffer
            Return 0
        End If

        If url_pos is less than url_buffer_size:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with url_buffer, url_pos, char
            Set url_pos to url_pos plus 1
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with url_buffer, url_pos, 0

    Note: Store both text and URL in metadata (concatenate with separator)
    Let total_length be text_pos plus url_pos plus 1  Note: +1 for separator
    Let combined_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with total_length plus 1

    If combined_buffer is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with text_buffer
        proc deallocate from Layout with url_buffer
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Copy text
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than text_pos:
        Let byte be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text_buffer, index
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with combined_buffer, index, byte
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add separator (null byte)
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with combined_buffer, index, 0
    Set index to index plus 1

    Note: Copy URL
    Let url_index be 0

    While url_index is less than url_pos:
        Set byte to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with url_buffer, url_index
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with combined_buffer, index, byte
        Set index to index plus 1
        Set url_index to url_index plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with combined_buffer, index, 0

    proc deallocate from Layout with text_buffer
    proc deallocate from Layout with url_buffer

    Let token_type be TOKEN_LINK

    If is_image is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to TOKEN_IMAGE
    End If

    Return proc create_token with token_type, combined_buffer, total_length, line, column, text_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recognizes CommonMark autolinks of the form "<url>" — angle-bracket delimited
URLs with no spaces or newlines inside. Space inside the brackets aborts
because that would indicate inline HTML or accidentally captured tag content
that the downstream HTML-block scanner should claim instead.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_autolink" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan autolink: <url>

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Skip <
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let buffer_size be 512
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Return 0
        End If

        If char is equal to 62:  Note: is greater than (closing)
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Return 0
        End If

        If char is equal to 32:  Note: Space (not allowed in autolink)
            proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
            Return 0
        End If

        If buffer_pos is less than buffer_size:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_AUTOLINK, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Token Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The main dispatch. Order matters: EOF first (so an empty document yields a
clean TOKEN_EOF), then newline (LF and CRLF normalized to one TOKEN_NEWLINE),
then block-level scanners are tried only when at_line_start = 1 (the
CommonMark prerequisite for blocks), then inline scanners are always
attempted. Anything that no scanner claims becomes a single-character
TOKEN_TEXT — the parser is responsible for coalescing adjacent text tokens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Block-level scanners that fail (return 0) leave the cursor unchanged so the
fallthrough to inline scanning sees the same byte. CRLF is collapsed by
absorbing the LF after emitting NEWLINE on the CR.
@End Implementation
Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from lexer

    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer
    Let at_line_start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Check for EOF
    If char is equal to 0:
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: Check for newline
    If char is equal to 10:  Note: \n
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NEWLINE, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 13:  Note: \r
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer

        Note: Check for \r\n
        Let next_char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If next_char is equal to 10:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If

        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NEWLINE, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: Block-level tokens (only at line start)
    If at_line_start is equal to 1:
        Note: Try heading
        If char is equal to 35:  Note: #
            Let token be proc scan_heading with lexer

            If token is not equal to 0:
                Return token
            End If
        End If

        Note: Try code fence
        If char is equal to 96:  Note: `
            Set token to proc scan_code_fence with lexer

            If token is not equal to 0:
                Return token
            End If
        End If

        If char is equal to 126:  Note: ~
            Set token to proc scan_code_fence with lexer

            If token is not equal to 0:
                Return token
            End If
        End If

        Note: Try blockquote
        If char is equal to 62:  Note: >
            Set token to proc scan_blockquote with lexer

            If token is not equal to 0:
                Return token
            End If
        End If

        Note: Try list marker
        Set token to proc scan_list_marker with lexer

        If token is not equal to 0:
            Return token
        End If

        Note: Try horizontal rule
        Set token to proc scan_horizontal_rule with lexer

        If token is not equal to 0:
            Return token
        End If
    End If

    Note: Inline elements (can occur anywhere)
    Set char to proc peek_char with lexer

    Note: Try inline code
    If char is equal to 96:  Note: `
        Set token to proc scan_inline_code with lexer

        If token is not equal to 0:
            Return token
        End If
    End If

    Note: Try emphasis or strong (* or **)
    If char is equal to 42:  Note: *
        Set token to proc scan_emphasis_or_strong with lexer, 42

        If token is not equal to 0:
            Return token
        End If
    End If

    Note: Try emphasis or strong (_ or __)
    If char is equal to 95:  Note: _
        Set token to proc scan_emphasis_or_strong with lexer, 95

        If token is not equal to 0:
            Return token
        End If
    End If

    Note: Try link or image
    If char is equal to 33:  Note: ! (image)
        Set next_char to proc peek_char_at with lexer, 1

        If next_char is equal to 91:  Note: ![
            Set token to proc scan_link_or_image with lexer, 1

            If token is not equal to 0:
                Return token
            End If
        End If
    End If

    If char is equal to 91:  Note: [ (link)
        Set token to proc scan_link_or_image with lexer, 0

        If token is not equal to 0:
            Return token
        End If
    End If

    Note: Try autolink
    If char is equal to 60:  Note: <
        Set token to proc scan_autolink with lexer

        If token is not equal to 0:
            Return token
        End If
    End If

    Note: Default: text token (single character)
    Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let text_ptr be source plus position

    proc advance_char with lexer

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TEXT, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
End Process

Note: End of Markdown Lexer
